t“I Confess: I Was the Girl in the Shadows” -- tQueer Auto-Porn-Art: Genealogies, Aesthetics, Ethics, and Desire -- tOn Not Seeing All: The Incomplete, Sexual Play, and the Ethics of the Frame -- tTo Queer Things Up: Sexing the Self in the Queer Documentary Web Series -- tA Man with a Mother: Tarnation and the Subject of Confession -- tLooking, Stroking, and Speaking: A Queer Ethics of MAP Desire -- tPlaying Confession: Gaming, Autobiography, and the Elusive Self -- tFrom a “Disappeared Aesthetics” to a “Trans-Aesthetics”: Derek Jarman and Ming Wong’s Image-Based Technologies of the Self -- tWriting Intimacy: Fantasy, New Media, and Confession in Marie Calloway’s what purpose did I serve in your life -- tHentai Confessions: Transgression and “Sexual Technologies of the Self” in Akihiko Shiota’s Moonlight Whispers -- tPorno-Graphing: “Dirtiness” and Self-Objectification -- tShut Me Up in Grindr: Anti-confessional Discourse and Sensual Nonsense in MSM Media -- tFigures -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the postwar decades, sexual revolutions - first women's suffrage, flappers, Prohibition, and Mae West; later Alfred Kinsey, Hugh Hefner, and the pill - altered the lifestyles and desires of generations. Since the 1990s, the internet and its cataclysmic cultural and social technological shifts have unleashed a third sexual revolution, crystallized in the acts and rituals of confession that are a staple of our twenty-first-century lives. In I Confess!, a collection of thirty original essays, leading international scholars such as Ken Plummer, Susanna Paasonen, Tom Roach, and Shohini Ghosh explore the ideas of confession and sexuality in moving image arts and media, mostly in the Global North, over the last quarter century. Through self-referencing or autobiographical stories, testimonies, and performances, and through rigorously scrutinized case studies of "gay for pay," gaming, camming, YouTube uploads, and the films Tarnation and Nymph()maniac, the contributors describe a spectrum of identities, desires, and related representational practices. Together these desires and practices shape how we see, construct, and live our identities within this third sexual revolution, embodying both its ominous implications of surveillance and control and its utopian glimmers of community and liberation. Inspired by theorists from Michel Foucault and Gilles Deleuze to Gayle Rubin and José Esteban Muñoz, I Confess! reflects an extraordinary, paradigm-shifting proliferation of first-person voices and imagery produced during the third sexual revolution, from the eve of the internet to today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / General.2bisacsh1 aArroyo, Brandon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArroyo, Brandon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aArseneault, jordan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharbonneau, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Szegheo-lang, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Villiers, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenzel, Valentina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aE.S. Sinwell, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvoy, Jacob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalardeau, Éric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhosh, Shohini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJandl, Silke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 